The impossibility of discovering a passage in Plato, which in the least suggests the argument for immortality drawn from the unlimited capaci- ties of the mind, has been passed over in silence by the commentators, although they retain the words Haec Platonis fere, after recordari, 1. 20. In Τ. l). 1, 66, Cicero quotes a parallel passage from his Consolatio, which was based upon Crantor, who wrote the first commentaries on Plato, and in his amplifications of Platonic teaching may possibly have suggested this train of thought to Cicero.
